{% block content %}
  <h2>Where it stands</h2>
  <p>In the 2021 Census, about 1,160 people in Robinson Huron Treaty territory could speak the language, and only about 545 spoke it at home. Across the country, the number of Ojibway-language speakers fell more than 5 percent between 2016 and 2021, and many people carry the language as a mother tongue without being able to hold a conversation in it. These are small numbers, and they are the reason the work is urgent.</p>

  <h2>What is being done</h2>
  <p>The 21 Robinson Huron Treaty nations are building a shared Anishinaabemowin reclamation strategy, funded by interest from the annuities settlement, reported at about $16 million over three years. It is one of the most hopeful things to come out of the settlement: the nations choosing, together, to put treaty money toward the language. Local institutions carry this work too, including the Ojibwe Cultural Foundation in M'Chigeeng, which has been a language hub since 1974 and runs its own Ojibwe-language radio, and Kenjgewin Teg.</p>

  <h2>On this site</h2>
  <p>We use Anishinaabemowin in our own dialect where we can, drawing first on local and community sources and on the Nishnaabemwin Online Dictionary of the Lake Huron and Manitoulin language. Our word list grows over time, and Elders and language keepers guide it. We never invent or machine-translate a word; where nothing sourced exists, we leave the English. If you see something we can say better, tell us.</p>

